Incidents Responded to Across the City of Austin

Annie Fu (UT EID: arf2742)

Introduction

This report will be an extension of the last report by only focusing on one data set (the number of incidents that were responded to) from the public database that the City of Austin provides (https://data.austintexas.gov/). Interest was sparked to continue to explore this dataset as it was found that there were a a lot of months that didnt meat compliance requirements, meaning that a lot of ambulances didnt arrive quick enough.

Each row for this dataset represents an observation made in a month of a specific year from October 2010 to January 2023. The variables that the Incidents dataset contains are Month.Key (formatted YYYYMM), Month.Year (formatted MON YEAR), Total.Incidents (the total number of incidents responded to), Austin.Incidents (the total number of incidents in the city of Austin), Travis.County.Incidents (the total number of incidents in Travis County), Other.Area.Incidents (the total number of incidents not in the city of Austin or Travis County), Combined.Austin.and.Travis.County.Incidents (the total combined number of incidents in the city of Austin and Travis County), Austin.P1.Incidents ~ Austin.P5.Incidents (the total number of incidents based on priority level in the city of Austin where P1 is the most sever and P5 is the least), Travis.County.P1.Incidents ~ Travis.County.P5.Incidents (the total number of incidents based on priority level in Travis County), Overall.On.Time.Compliance (the percentage of ambulances that arrived on time in all of Austin), Austin.On.Time.Compliance (the percentage of ambulances that arrived on time in the city of Austin), Travis.County.On.Time.Compliance (the percentage of ambulances that arrived on time in Travis County), Austin.P1.On.Time.Compliance ~ Austin.P5.On.Time.Compliance (the percentage of ambulances that arrived on time depending on priority level in the city of Austin), Travis.County.P1.On.Time.Compliance ~ Travis.County.P5.On.Time.Compliance (the percentage of ambulances that arrived on time depending on the priority levels in Travis County), and Target.On.Time.Compliance (the target percentage of ambulances that should arrive on time).

Due to the many different variables, a lot of different potential relationships can be explored: how location can impact the number of ambulances sent out, whether priority level incidents may be affected by location, or whether the number of incidents a city has affects how quickly an ambulance can arrive.

Considering all of the potential relationships that can be explored, the following question was crafted: How well does the year (Year), the priority level of patients (Priority), and the total number of incidents for those priority levels (Incidents) predict whether or not the target compliance was met for a particular month of a year?

Its predicted that these three variables may be good predictors of the target compliance. It may be seen that the higher the number of incidents for any priority level that have been answered to, the less likely that target compliance was met (same with the the increase in severity of priority level and increase in years).

# load packages
library(tidyverse)

library(caret)

library(cluster)
library(factoextra)

# Save the data as a dataframe
incidents <- read.csv("incidents.csv")

Tidying/Wrangling of Incidents Dataset

Before the Incidents dataset can be tidied/wrangled, the observations for the separate location priority levels (Austin and Travis County) had to be combined. The incidents were added together while the compliances were recalculated with the following equation: \[\frac{COA.Priority.Comp/100 * COA.Priority.Incidents + TC.Priority.Comp/100 * TC.Priority.Incidents}{Total.COA.and.TC.Priority.Incidents}\] Furthermore, all of the individual columns of the priority levels (such as Austin.P1.Incidents) were removed.

#recalculate priority level incidents and compliances
incidents1 <- incidents %>%
  #combine the priority level incidents
  mutate("P1.Incidents" = Travis.County.P1.Incidents + Austin.P1.Incidents,
         "P2.Incidents" = Travis.County.P2.Incidents + Austin.P2.Incidents,
         "P3.Incidents" = Travis.County.P3.Incidents + Austin.P3.Incidents,
         "P4.Incidents" = Travis.County.P4.Incidents + Austin.P4.Incidents,
         "P5.Incidents" = Travis.County.P5.Incidents + Austin.P5.Incidents,
         #find total compliances of each priority level
         "P1.Compliance" = 100 * (Austin.P1.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Austin.P1.Incidents + Travis.County.P1.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Travis.County.P1.Incidents)/P1.Incidents,
         "P2.Compliance" = 100 * (Austin.P2.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Austin.P2.Incidents + Travis.County.P2.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Travis.County.P2.Incidents)/P2.Incidents,
         "P3.Compliance" = 100 * (Austin.P3.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Austin.P3.Incidents + Travis.County.P3.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Travis.County.P3.Incidents)/P3.Incidents,
         "P4.Compliance" = 100 * (Austin.P4.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Austin.P4.Incidents + Travis.County.P4.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Travis.County.P4.Incidents)/P4.Incidents,
         "P5.Compliance" = 100 * (Austin.P5.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Austin.P5.Incidents + Travis.County.P5.On.Time.Compliance/100 * Travis.County.P5.Incidents)/P5.Incidents) %>%
  #remove the individual incidents and compliance counts
  select(-c("Austin.P1.Incidents":"Travis.County.P5.Incidents"), -c("Austin.P1.On.Time.Compliance":"Travis.County.P5.On.Time.Compliance"))

Then, to tidy the dataset, the pivot_longer() was used to combine all of the necessary columns into the format of priority.type with their values. separate() was then used to split the priority.type column into Priority (the priority level of the incidents) and Type (whether it was incidents or compliance) and to split the Month.Year column into Month and Year.

#condense columns into one
incidents1 <- incidents1 %>%
  #create priority and type columns
  pivot_longer(cols = c("P1.Incidents":"P5.Compliance"),
               names_to = "priority.type",
               values_to = "Count") %>%
  separate(priority.type, 
           into = c( "Priority", "Type"),
           convert = TRUE) %>%
  #create month and year columns
  separate(Month.Year, 
           into = c( "Month", "Year"),
           convert = TRUE)

Exploratory Data Analysis

Before any data exploration could be done, the Priority column had to be mutated from a character class type to a numeric value (i.e.P1 = 1).

#manipulate outcome variable and character variables into values
incidents1 %>%
  mutate(Priority = case_when(Priority == "P1" ~ 1,
                              Priority == "P2" ~ 2,
                              Priority == "P3" ~ 3,
                              Priority == "P4" ~ 4,
                              Priority == "P5" ~ 5)) -> incidents1

A correlation matrix was then created to see which pairs of variables are the most/least correlated out of the variables that are being explored in this report (Year, Incidents, Priority, and Compliance).

#correlation matrix of incidents1
ggcorrplot(cor(incidents1 %>%
                 select(Priority, Year, Incidents, Compliance)),
           type = "upper", # upper diagonal
           lab = TRUE, # print values
           method = "circle")

The pair of variables that had the greatest correlation was Compliance and Priority with the largest correlation magnitude value (0.52). The least correlated pair of variables is Year and Priority with the smallest correaltion magnitude value (0). This makes sense since there were emergencies for each priority level every year meaning that there would be no relationship between the two variables whereas there could be very different compliance levels among priority levels since a late ambulance for different priority levels could mean life or death of a patient.

Furthermore, visualizations were made to observe the relationship between each predictor variable compared to the outcome variable.

#bar graph of average compliance for each priority level
ggplot(incidents1, aes(x = as.character(Priority), y = Compliance, fill = as.character(Priority))) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "summary", fun = "mean") + 
  labs(title = "Bar Graph Distribution of Priority Levels and Compliance",
       x = "Priority Levels",
       y = "Average Compliance (%)",
       fill = "Priority Levels")

This visualization is of a bar graph comparing the average compliance percentages of each of the priority levels. Based on the graph, there seems to be a trend that as the severity of the priority level decreases (where priority level 5 is less severe compared to priority level 1) as the average compliance percentage increases from left to right (with the exception of priority level 5). Thus, there is some negative correlation between the priority levels and compliance (in terms of severity of the patient vs compliance; otherwise, there is a positive correlation between the numeric values of the priority level and compliance).

#scatterplot of priority incidents with compliance
ggplot(incidents1, aes(x = Incidents, y = Compliance)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Relationship Between Priority Incidents and Compliance",
       x = "Number of Incidents with Different Priority Levels",
       y = "Compliance (met or not met)")

This visualization depicts the relationship between the the number of incidents with the different priority levels within a month and their compliance. It confirms that there is a positive correlation between the priority incidents and compliance percentage that the correlation matrix demonstrated as there is a positive trend shown by the blue line.

#scatterplot of compliance percentage over the years
ggplot(incidents1, aes(x = Year, y = Compliance)) +
  geom_point()+ 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2010,2023,1)) + 
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Year and Compliance",
       x = "Year", 
       fill = "Compliance (met or not)")

This visualization shows how the compliance percentage changes over the years. Over time, it seems that the spread of compliance seems to get larger, thus causing an average decrease over the years. As a result, there seems to be a negative trend between compliance and year which supports the negative correlation found in the correlation matrix.

Prediction and Cross-Validation

Before any predictions can be made, the Compliance column had to mutated into a binary variable where 1 indicated that the target compliance level was met (>90) and 0 indicated that the target compliance level was not met.

#create binary variable out of compliance
incidents1 %>%
  mutate(Compliance = ifelse(Compliance > 90, 1, 0)) -> incidents1

Since there seemed to some grouping among the priority incidents vs complaince visualization, I opted to use the k-nearest neighbor (kNN) model for predictions.

# Consider the kNN classifier with k = 5
incidents_kNN <- knn3(Compliance ~ Priority + Year + Incidents,
                      data = incidents1, 
                      k = 5) # number of neighbors

#ROC model for predictions
incidents_ROC <- ggplot(incidents1) + 
  geom_roc(aes(d = Compliance, m = predict(incidents_kNN, incidents1)[,2]), n.cuts = 10)
incidents_ROC #to create ROC model

#find AUC value
calc_auc(incidents_ROC)
##   PANEL group       AUC
## 1     1    -1 0.9649377

Both the ROC curve (line reaches close towards 1 on the true positive axis) and AUC value (0.9649377) demonstrate that the kNN model classifier is doing a pretty good job at predicting whether or not compliance will be met for a particular month. However, cross-validation will be done to ensure that the classifier is a good classifier and measure to predict the data.

# Cross validation for the kNN model
kNN_cv <- train(as.factor(Compliance) ~ Priority + Total.Incidents + Incidents,
      data = incidents1,
      method = "knn",
      trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)) # 10-fold cv

# Let's take a look at the output
kNN_cv

The accuracy seems to average around 0.9/0.91 as new values are calculated into the model. As more data gets added into the data, the accuracy seems to improve; thus, it is safe to believe that the kNN classifier does predict the new observations pretty well. However, since the accuracy is relatively high but not as high as 0.97, this means that there are small signs that could indicate that overfitting was done, but it would be difficult to tell since an accuracy level of around 0.9/0.91 is still pretty high.

Dimension Reduction

A Principal Component Analysis (PCA) model is performed by selecting all of the columns that are numeric and removing the Target.On.Time.Compliance and Month.Key columns (these two columns are more used as definition variables where one column defines the target goal compliance while the other column defines the month/year of when the observations were recorded). Before the PCA could be done, though, the numeric variables were scaled by subtracting the mean from each variable and then dividing by the standard deviation.

#PCA model
incidents_pca <- incidents1 %>% 
  select(is.numeric, -Target.On.Time.Compliance, -Month.Key) %>%
  scale %>%
  prcomp

A scree plot was created to visualize the variance created by each component and to determine the number of principal components that would be used.

# Visualize percentage of variance explained for each PC in a scree plot
fviz_eig(incidents_pca, addlabels = TRUE, ylim = c(0, 50))

The principal component values indicate the percent variance that those particular PCs account for regarding the data. Scoring high for the first two PCs means that the first two PCs account for most of the variance of the data and vice versa for scoring low (first two PCs dont account for as much of the variance of the data to where more PCs have to be retained).

Added together, the first two components added up to roughly 60.3% meaning that roughly 60.1% of the variance in the data is accounted for by the first two components. Adding in the third principal component, the amount of variance that is accounted for is roughly 73.3%; thus, the first three components should be retained as the aim is to keep around 80% of the variance. Looking at the scree plot, it seems that PC1 contributes the most of the variation of the data, PC2 contributes the next most, and PC3 contributes the 3rd most. With this pattern, it can be inferred that the later PCs contribute less and less.

Afterwards, the observations were visualized using the first two PCs.

# Top contributions of the variables to the PC as a percentage
fviz_contrib(incidents_pca, choice = "var", axes = 1, top = 3) # on PC1

fviz_contrib(incidents_pca, choice = "var", axes = 2, top = 3) # on PC2

# Visualize the individuals according to PC1 and PC2
fviz_pca_ind(incidents_pca, repel = TRUE)

Looking at the visualizations of the first two PCs, it can be determined that Total.Incidents contributes the most to the variance accounted for by the first component and that Compliance accounts for most of the variance covered by the second component. There also seems to imply that a majority of observations negatively correlate with both PCs which can be furthered examined through a correlation circle to determine what variables may have pushed these observations to be negatively correlated.

# Visualize both variables and individuals in the same graph
fviz_pca_var(incidents_pca, col.var = "blue", 
             repel = TRUE) # Avoid text overlapping of the variable names

Before interpreting the correlation circle, it must be established first that contributing negatively to a component means that there is a negative correlation between the principal component and the variable. On the other hand, contributing positively means that there is a positive correlation between a principal component and variable.

Looking at the correlation circle, the variables Other.Area.Incidents, Austin.Incidents, Total.Incidents, Combined.Austin.and.Travis.County.Incidents, Travis.County.Incidents, and Incidents contribute to the first component positively while Priority, Compliance, Travis.On.Time.Compliance, Overall.On.Time.Compliance, and Austin.On.Time.Compliance contribute negatively to the first component.

On the other hand, the variable Other.Area.Incidents is the only variable that contributes positively to the second component while Austin.Incidents, Total.Incidents, Combined.Austin.and.Travis.County.Incidents, Travis.County.Incidents, Incidents, Priority, Compliance, Travis.On.Time.Compliance, Overall.On.Time.Compliance, and Austin.On.Time.Compliance contribute negatively to the second component.

Clustering

As the kNN model was used to construct the relationship between the variables, the k-means clustering method was used to predict whether or not compliance was met. First the optimal number of clusters was determined.

#scale data
incidents_scaled <- incidents1 %>% 
  select(Compliance, Priority, Incidents, Year) %>%
  scale

# Maximize the silhouette while keeping a small number of clusters
fviz_nbclust(incidents_scaled, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

As a result, 10 clusters was determined to be optimal for creating a cluster graph of the data.

# Use the function kmeans() to find clusters
kmeans_results <- incidents1 %>% 
  select(Priority, Incidents, Year) %>%
  scale %>%
  kmeans(centers = 10) # change to 6 centers

# Visualize the clusters
fviz_cluster(kmeans_results, data = incidents1 %>% select(Priority, Incidents, Year))

# Let's visualize the clusters
incidents1 %>%
  mutate(cluster = as.factor(kmeans_results$cluster)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = Incidents, color = cluster, shape = as.character(Priority))) + 
  geom_point()  +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2010,2023,1)) + 
  labs(title = "Cluster Plot",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Number of Incidents of each Priority Level (per month)",
       color = "Cluster",
       shape = "Priority")

Based on the cluster plot with the top 2 PCs of just the three variables, there seems to be a relatively clear separation between the ten different clusters. Nonetheless, it seems difficult to apply that cluster plot with the data, thus ggplot() was used to further examine the clusters and how they relate to the variables being examined.

After fitting the variables using ggplot() for a clearer interpretation, it seems to be that the clusters divide the priority levels, for the most part, into smaller groups from their original priority level clusters. Take Priority Level 4 as an example where it is divided between 4 different clusters, meaning that the priority levels are spread out far enough to where there are multiple means within a priority level. There also seems to be some overlap between priority levels and clusters, but overall, the clusters do a pretty good job at separating the clusters into their original priority levels.

Across the board, the ggplot() demonstrates how there are constant fluctuations between number of incidents for each cluster over time, but it also demonstrates that the more severe the priority level, the lower the amount of incidents that occur (priority level 1 is near the lower half of the y-axis and priority level 4 is near the upper half of the y-axis).

Discussion

The combination of the three variables (Priority level of the patient, the number of incidents responded to for each priority level, and year) seemed to predict well of whether or not compliance goal was met according to the kNN model that was done. The AUC value of the kNN model was 0.9649377, indicating that the three variables were good predictors of the outcome variable. However, when cross-validation was performed, it demonstrated that the kNN values had an accuracy of around 0.9/0.91 meaning that the kNN model isnt as accurate as I would like since there may have been some slight overfitting that occurred. However, it would be inconclusive to determine that there was overfitting that happened since the accuracy is still quite high. Looking at the correlation circle of the PC models, it seems that all three of these variables had some strength in terms of accounting for the variation in the data. Meanwhile, the cluster plots indicate that there are groups within the data that differ slightly from their original grouping, but each of the groups or clusters seem to have similar relationships between priority level incidents and total incidents. This means that these variables may have the same effect within the clusters across the board on whether the compliance requirement set was met.
